      <title>PvP and chokeholding a server</title>
      <link>http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=PVP&amp;message.id=10206#M10206</link>
      <description>Hi, this is a fairly serious topic that I have seen discussed a lot, but not very much has been done to adress it.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Currently, the rules regarding when disputes should be settled by PvP vs by PnP were outlined by Kefyra after wording her request in a way to get a specific answer.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Those rules are the worst set of rules to ever guide a PvP server.  It makes PvP nothing more than a total zerg number fest, takes away any strategy element, and makes guilds who are not at the top of progression absolutely irrelevant.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Let's assume for a minute, Ascending Dawn decided to war a guild lower in progression then them.  With the extremly asine rules that were layed out, AD would have total freedom to wreck every single raid by the lower level guild, take their mob and laugh at them, and should the lower level guild try to retaliate by attacking Ascending Dawn on a raid, AD could just petition a GM and ask a GM to give a warning to all of the opposing guild, for attacking a mob without sufficient force to kill it.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;This is incredibly asine, and leads to an effect where who is on top now can attack anyone's raids at their leisure, while claiming immunity from any attack, because the content they are doing is beyond whoever is likely to attack them.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;On RZ, time and time again, a little guild would win fights against bigger guild, through better PvP skill, stronger perseverance, more willingness to fight and go on without raiding.  Under the current rule set, a big guild could petition to have all its raids PvP free, since smaller guilds clearly are not likely to be able to take targets that bigger guilds raid.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;The reason why I draw a line between training and attacking people engaged is based on a simple philosophy.  When a guild choose to engage in an event, knowing full well that there are other guilds who are aggressive towards them, they make the conscious choice of 'exposing' themselves to PvP, and be ready for PvP to be brought on them.  Training on the other hand is something that is brought upon a guild who did nothing to facilitate it.  If someone choose to run into mobs and feigns death low on health, that's that person's fault for running into mobs, he went ahead and made himself vulnerable by this action.  If someone decides to experience in a zone where he can be attacked, that's his choice, but he knows that makes him more vulnerable to attacks.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;The definition that the only time of PvP acceptable is 100 vs 100 is stupid, because those type of fights have almost zero tactics, devolve into massive zergfests, and are decided sheerly by numbers, and it also skews the server to force people to form zerg alliance in their own time zone just to stay competitive.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Among the top four guilds, Hate, Defiant, Ascending Dawn, PDM, Hate for example is the only guild to not have progressed past Qvic, or having won any MPG trials/RS royalty.  They however are probably the guild who is the most used to dealing with disruption on their events, which should be a huge advantage.  Defiant and PDM have formed an alliance, and raid together with numbers well beyond what any single guild on their timezone is able to field.  Does this mean that when Defiant and PDM are zerging RS royalty with 100+ in zone, they should not be attacked by any guild who cannot field 100+ themselves?  This type of enforcement of only allowing straight up PvP cheapens the entire Pvp experience.  People become just numbers, you cannot have clever tactics.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Every time PDM has been defeated through the use of superior strategy, they have petitioned a GM complaining about how unfair the tactics used against them where, yet when servers crash, they quickly hurry outside an instance to pick off people as they log back in and are booted outside before they gain control, this is smart, it is attacking people while they are the most vulnerable.  I am fine with this tactic, but if killing people while they are ungrouped after an incident which they had no control over is fine, why is attacking people after they intentionally made themselves more vulnerable frowned upon?</description>
