    <item>
      <title>Re: PvP and chokeholding a server</title>
      <link>http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=PVP&amp;message.id=10283#M10283</link>
      <description>&lt;DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;HR&gt;&#xD;
&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;EM&gt;&lt;STRONG&gt;However, if I zoned in and they hadn't yet engaged the boss, I would see it as perfectly&amp;nbsp;fair to engage them. I don't care how many people I have, and don't see that as relevant in any way. I am thinking of Camby's suggestion that I should have to have 50% of my opponents force or I shouldnt attack. &amp;nbsp;If I have too few people and get crushed, that is my problem. Whether I have enough is a personal judgement. 2 groups can cause a raid of 50 a lot of problems after all.&lt;/STRONG&gt;&lt;/EM&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;HR&gt;&#xD;
&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;There is absolutely nothing wrong with this Raitsila,&amp;nbsp;if your guild's 2 groups want to run a suicide mission against a raid force of 60, that's perfectly with in your rights.&amp;nbsp; The problem lies in how and when you attend to launch your attack.&amp;nbsp; If you choose to train all the npc's from the zone line to your enemies raid force, this is wrong.&amp;nbsp; If you choose to attack the raid force after they have engaged their raid objective ( Raid Level Mob as Defined by SoE ) by mezzing / killing your enemies members while engaged on their objective, this is wrong.&amp;nbsp; You are within your rights if they chose to attack you when they are already engaged, to defend yourself appropriately, remembering in doing so that you do your best to avoid causing undo experience deaths.&amp;nbsp; If a enemy ranger attacks you, you can kill him, if his cleric heals him, you can kill the cleric too, but if the ranger attacks and you Manaburn the Main Tank, this is wrong.&amp;nbsp; The intention of the 50% balance of your enemies raid force only serves the purpose to constitute the legitimacy of an attack of one guild vs. another guild over an objective MoB.&amp;nbsp; Lets give an example for the sake of argument.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;Lets say PDM is preparing to engage the CBQ with 70 people.&amp;nbsp; In zones a group of Hate, but PDM has yet to engage CBQ.&amp;nbsp; Hate is more than welcome to attack PDM, even greatly outnumbered as they may be.&amp;nbsp; The Hate get pwned but they continue to return to the zone, over and over again, harassing PDM and not allowing them to engage the CBQ.&amp;nbsp; If PDM then does engage the CBQ and Hate attacks using the excuse " we were already engaged in PvP " even after they have warp hacked / succored away from PvP and subsequently cause PDM to wipe the raid, Hate has broken the PnP.&amp;nbsp; ONLY if Hate had a substantial force of 35 ( 1/2 of PDM's numbers ) should they be allowed to legitimately fight PDM for the rights to CBQ or subsequently to stop PDM's progression.&amp;nbsp; One group coming back again and again isn't PvP, its griefing.&amp;nbsp; If you intend on fighting your enemy for a MoB or to stop them from doing a MoB, then you should STAY and FIGHT, not run / harass / run / harass / run / harass.&amp;nbsp; To do this is an exploit of the PnP, this is why on Vallon we had our LnS rule.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; Everquest PvP has to be balanced with PvE to keep the game exciting.&amp;nbsp; Without the Play Nice Policies, Zek would be in a state of anarchy, there would be no progression, we'd all simply be running around Nektulos forest in our patchwork tunics weilding tarnished 2 handed swords at level 10.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;HR&gt;&#xD;
&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;Long story short, when engaging in PvP you should ask yourself these 3 questions:&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;1.&amp;nbsp; Do we have an adequate force to fight this guild and stand any legitimate chance of winning if&amp;nbsp;our enemy wasn't engaged in PvE&amp;nbsp;?&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;2.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Can we reasonably engage&amp;nbsp;without causing&amp;nbsp;undo experience loss to our enemies ?&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;3.&amp;nbsp; Do we have an adequate force to fight the Target NPC ?&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;If the answer is NO to any of these 3 questions, then you shouldn't&amp;nbsp;disrupt the &lt;STRONG&gt;main raid force &lt;/STRONG&gt;with PvP.&amp;nbsp; You might argue&amp;nbsp;that you are after the same Target NPC as your enemy, but&amp;nbsp;if you cannot gain&amp;nbsp;control of&amp;nbsp;the spawn&amp;nbsp;by&amp;nbsp;reasonable and&amp;nbsp;legitimate means, then&amp;nbsp;you are just SoL.&amp;nbsp; Kill them after the MoB is dead or before they reach their target.&amp;nbsp; You might lose with lower numbers, but you might slow their progression enough to allow more of your own to log on and actually contend for the Target.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;HR&gt;&#xD;
&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;These 3 questions are guidelines that if you are willing to adhere to the PnP's that you can use as guidelines of engagement.&amp;nbsp; If you want to attack your enemy, do so with the intent to actually &lt;STRONG&gt;fight &lt;/STRONG&gt;him/her, not fight until you have to gate, then return and repeat over and over.&amp;nbsp; If you are beat, then stay beat and if you win, your enemy needs to bow out and do the same.&lt;/DIV&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;</description>
      <pubDate>Fri, 25 Feb 2005 02:25:40 GMT</pubDate>
